For sub with `vpminud`, the canonical approach is:
```
t = lhs + (2^32 - rhs)  // = lhs - rhs mod 2^32, unsigned
// t is in [0, 2^32 - 1]
// If no borrow (lhs >= rhs): t = lhs - rhs in [0, P-1] → canonical
// If borrow (lhs < rhs): t = 2^32 - rhs + lhs = 2^32 + (lhs - rhs), which is 2^32 - (rhs - lhs) in [2^32 - P + 1, 2^32 - 1]
//   → need to add P: t + P = 2^32 - (rhs - lhs) + P, mod 2^32 = P - (rhs - lhs) = lhs - rhs + P ✓
// But alternatively:
t = lhs - rhs  // in [0, P-1] if no borrow, in very large values if borrow
canonical = t + P  // always computed
result = vpminud(t, canonical)  // picks the smaller
// If no borrow: t in [0, P-1], canonical = t+P in [P, 2P-1] → result = t ✓
// If borrow: t = 2^32 - (rhs - lhs) in [2^32 - P + 1, 2^32 - 1], canonical = t + P wraps!
```

The problem is that when there's a borrow, `t + P` might wrap beyond 2^32. So `vpminud` doesn't work directly for sub. That's why the old sub used `vpcmpltud` (comparison) + `vpaddd_masked`.

